{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Cron parser rejects invalid expressions with descriptive errors.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is deterministic validation logic at a single parser boundary. Invalid field ranges/syntax and error text can be reproduced by direct function inputs; no I/O, OS, network, or model dependency is required.","test_description":"Call the parser directly with invalid cron strings (`* * * 13 *`, `* * 32 * *`, malformed token counts, bad symbols) and assert structured error type/code plus message fragments that identify the offending field/value.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.84,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Next-run-time calculator returns correct timestamps, including last-day-of-month and nearest-weekday cases.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The core risk is deterministic calendar math from a start instant and parsed schedule rule. Real failures are catchable at a pure computation boundary without external infra.","test_description":"Invoke the next-run calculator with fixed start timestamps and deterministic schedule objects for normal cron plus `L`/last-day and `W`/nearest-weekday semantics; assert exact next N timestamps for leap/non-leap months and weekend-adjustment edge cases.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.77,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Overlap detector flags schedules firing within minimum-gap windows and reports conflicts.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A pure mock of schedule outputs can hide real failures in how detector logic consumes actual generated run sequences from scheduling modules. Minimum realistic boundary is detector + run-time generation wired together.","test_description":"Create two real schedule definitions, generate upcoming fire times through the engine’s scheduling modules, run overlap detection with a 5-minute gap, and assert detected conflict windows (start/end pairs) and non-conflicts just outside threshold.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.74,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Timezone-aware scheduling handles DST spring-forward gap and fall-back ambiguity for a 2:30 AM job.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Correctness depends on real timezone/DST behavior from platform tzdata and runtime time APIs. Mocking timezone transitions often masks true failures around nonexistent/ambiguous local times.","test_description":"Run end-to-end scheduling computation using real timezone data (e.g., `America/New_York`) across concrete DST dates: spring-forward day where 2:30 AM is nonexistent and fall-back day where 2:30 AM is ambiguous. Assert engine behavior matches configured policy for gap/ambiguity resolution and produced UTC instants are correct.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.26,"System":0.69,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When next run is in the past, engine applies missed-run policy (skip vs backfill) correctly.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failures usually occur at policy + scheduler-state wiring (last run, now, computed next, queue decision), not in one isolated function. In-process mocks can hide sequencing/state bugs.","test_description":"With a local persistence fixture (or in-memory repository used by production modules), set job state so next run is already past, execute scheduling decision flow for `skip` and `backfill` policies, and assert resulting enqueued runs/state transitions differ as expected.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.28,"Integration":0.64,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]}
